SUMMARY:Splitting without Splitting (Tsvetelina Plummer\, Pricillia Gunawan
 ) from AmA Conference
DESCRIPTION:This episode will be streamed live from Agile meets Architectur
 e conference https://www.agile-meets-architecture.com/ .\n\nWe all know it 
 - our team has become too big\, meetings take too long\, half of the conver
 sations don’t apply to our work\, and the sprint goal is now “finish all st
 ories in the sprint”! The classic textbook and the chatbot are certain: The
  team should be split!\n\nAnd this is indeed the optimal solution. But real
  life isn’t a textbook\, and our resources aren’t infinite. What if instead
  of slicing to be a-two-pizza-team\, we asked the question: “What do we act
 ually need to work well together?”\n\nAfter over 4 years working with sever
 al large data science and engineering teams that wrestled with multiple var
 iations of the same problem\, we’ve resisted the urge to split by the book.
 \n\nInstead of insisting on the one right way\, we want to show you how tun
 ing in\, listening\, and deliberately choosing the solution\, can bring bac
 k the fun\, ease and coveted efficiency we all are after.\n\nThat could mea
 n: changing who does what in the team\, redrawing team boundaries\, or comb
 ining pragmatic approaches of multiple organizational design systems like L
 eSS\, Team Topologies\, and Fluid Teams.\n\nThe trick is to stop chasing th
 e perfect model and start designing something that actually fits both the t
 eam’s culture and unique problem domain. Think of it like tailoring a suit:
  it has to fit the people wearing it\, not just look
